  "output": "That's fine to skip — I have enough to write up the analysis.\n\n## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\nThis is an async Python job-scraper (fetchers → filters → SQLite store → notifiers), not a React app, so I've adapted \"re-renders\" to the equivalent hot-path/repeated-work issues in this codebase.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:55-97` (`Store.diff`)\n\nFor every job in the batch, `diff()` does one `SELECT` then one `INSERT`/`UPDATE` — a full SQLite round-trip per row. Amazon/Microsoft/Netflix fetchers alone can return 300-1000+ postings per run, so a single pipeline run issues 600-2000+ individual statements where 2-3 would do.\n\n```python\n# current: one SELECT + one INSERT/UPDATE per job\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\n**Fix — batch the read, batch the writes:**\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):  # stay under SQLite's variable limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 900]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update(dict(cur.execute(q, chunk).fetchall()))\n\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    to_insert, to_update = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job); to_insert.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); to_update.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        else:\n            touched.append((now, job.key))\n\n    if to_insert:\n        cur.executemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key,...,:now,:now)\", to_insert)\n    if to_update:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\", to_update)\n    if touched:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", touched)\n\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns O(N) round-trips into O(N/900) reads + 3 `executemany` calls.\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job in `filters.py:11-41`\n\n`match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` and `_compile(include)` **inside the per-job loop** in `filter_jobs` (`filters.py:44-54`). Every job recompiles the same include/exclude regex list from scratch — O(jobs × keywords) compilations instead of O(keywords) once.\n\n```python\n# filters.py — current\ndef filter_jobs(jobs, rules):\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=rules.get(\"include_keywords\"), ...)]\n    # match() -> _compile(exclude), _compile(include) — recompiled every call\n```\n\n**Fix — compile once, reuse:**\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = [l.lower() for l in (rules.get(\"locations\") or [])]\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\n(and change `match()`'s signature to accept pre-compiled patterns instead of raw strings). With thousands of listings across companies this removes the single biggest avoidable CPU cost in the filter path.\n\n### 3. Redundant computation — `content_hash` computed twice per job — `models.py:66-75`, `store.py:67`\n\n`Store.diff` reads `job.content_hash` (a `@property` that does a SHA-256 hash, `models.py:66-69`) to compare against the stored value, then immediately calls `_insert`/`_update` → `job.to_row()`, which **recomputes `content_hash` again** (`models.py:75`). Each is cheap alone, but it's duplicate hashing on every new/changed job across every run.\n\n**Fix:** compute once and pass it through:\n\n```python\nh = job.content_hash\nrow = job.to_row(content_hash=h)   # accept a precomputed hash instead of recomputing\n```\n\nor simpler — cache it on the dataclass instance the first time it's accessed (`functools.cached_property`, dropping `slots=True` or using a manual cache field).\n\n### 4. Caching opportunity — full board re-fetch every run, no conditional requests\n\n`fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_netflix`, `fetch_amazon`, `fetch_google`, `fetch_meta`, `fetch_workday` (fetchers.py) all paginate the **entire** careers board on every scheduled run (every 12h per the recent commit `6ae8083`), even though `Store` already knows what's unchanged. Microsoft/Amazon alone can be 40 pages × 10 = 400 requests each, every run, forever.\n\nTwo concrete wins:\n- **Conditional HTTP** — several of these are plain GETs (Greenhouse, Ashby, Lever, etc. via `_simple`) that could send `If-None-Match`/`If-Modified-Since` using an ETag/Last-Modified cached in the `meta` table (`store.py` already has a generic key/value `meta` table — reuse it), short-circuiting to `304` when unchanged.\n- **Early pagination stop using `posted_at`** — for boards that return newest-first (Microsoft, Netflix, Amazon already sort `recent`/`timestamp`), once a page's oldest `posted_at` is older than the last stored `first_seen`/marker, stop paginating instead of walking to `max_pages`. Right now they only stop when a page returns zero *new* IDs (`fresh` empty), meaning a company with 1 new posting on page 1 still has to walk all `max_pages` if page content shifts — worth double-checking, but more importantly there's no early-exit using timestamp ordering, which would cut most runs down to 1-2 pages instead of the full board.\n\n### 5. Minor — SQLite pragmas — `store.py:36-41`\n\nNo `PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL` / `PRAGMA synchronous=NORMAL` is set. With the batched-write fix above this matters less, but WAL mode meaningfully speeds up the write-then-read pattern used by `next_seq`'s `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` (store.py:111-125) under the scheduled 12h cron + any concurrent `agent.py db-new`/`report-num` calls.\n\n```python\nself.conn.execute(\"PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL\")\nself.conn.execute(\"PRAGMA synchronous=NORMAL\")\n```\n\n### Not applicable\n- **React re-renders**: no frontend in this repo — it's a CLI/pipeline tool. Skipped.\n- **Memory leaks**: checked `fetch_all` (fetchers.py:767-788) — the `httpx.AsyncClient` is correctly closed in a `finally` block, and `Store`/`sqlite3.Connection` are used via context managers throughout. No leak found.\n\n### Priority order\n1. Batch `Store.diff` (#1) — biggest win, straightforward, zero behavior change.\n2. Precompile filter regex (#2) — trivial fix, real CPU savings at scale.\n3. Dedup `content_hash` computation (#3) — small but free.\n4. Conditional/early-exit fetching (#4) — highest potential savings (fewer HTTP calls against rate-limited third-party APIs) but needs per-source design care.\n",
